Parliament has not ratified the amendment for Tymosenko's release
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the charges of opposition leader Julia Tymosenko.
MEPs refused in second reading the draft amendment to reduce penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for reaching a disadvantageous deal with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must decide on the convicted woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the regime's political vengeance judgment and has provoked a process of suspected court bias also in the west.
The proposed annulment of paragraph 365 of Criminal Law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MEPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
