Feeding an obese child: Do not take breakfast and take charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 years have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren will have a weight above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models surrounding it is.
On tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is 50% more frequent than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner, according to survey conducted with awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a chance"
In the families of big kids, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case with most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents were finding time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 students from the Czech primary schools.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a chance", action supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 sixth to third students have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the absence, proper diet and insufficient physical exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed indicates, for example, eating breakfast 5 times a day - in case - lunch - taste - dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet," one of the survey results said.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of student families eat at the same time.
In most families, each one eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been observed is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from possibilities proposed according to their own taste and personal opinion.
“The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating.”
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming thing is, in particular, a high preference for sugary lemonades," the survey finds.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place just in front of white meat.
The children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Focus on health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
"During a survey of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not a chance' awareness session, a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet was assessed," the survey finds.
The most prominent was, for example, for sweet lemonades as children began to give preference to consumable water.
Children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour balls or potatoes).
