The need for speed Le Run is fighting across America.
Revision
Initially a problem-free race is transformed because of a set of stupid mistakes of people who have nothing to do with a routine morning trip to work.
This fulfils to some extent everyone’s ambition, but it doesn’t help if no one wants to do something else.
The new subtitled game The Run produced high expectations before its release.
He promised to take a new direction with the already old racing series Need for Speed and to release a kind of game from playable games that would not only count with points.
So we were curious how the passages are going to be added in which the main hero comes out of his car and does what he wants.
As is already done in the NFS series, the result is completely different from what we were expecting.
These are potentially arcade racing games but the whole shot down because of some unnecessary mistakes that have already existed for several years.
These are not really mistakes but rather the expression of an incomprehensible laziness on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are caught up in the adventure whose main hero Jack has characteristic problems and to solve them begins to participate in illegal races across America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco and your mission is to arrive first in New York.
The idea has some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than 50 races.
As a result, each race is done on a different route and the stages planned in different environments that differ quite well from each other and are interesting.
The player does not feel for a moment that the game offers him something identical.
Some environments are also pretty even though the graphical technical level is of the same type as the previous series.
This is not the end of the world.
But driving through the desert, in autumn landscapes or in highly snowy mountains is very visually pleasant.
The tests are also occasionally accompanied by an atypical element.
For example, in the desert you find yourself in a sandstorm that significantly diminishes your visibility.
Then in the mountains you need to be careful that an avalanche does not fall on you.
Besides this, the different races are well arranged behind each other.
There are only a small number, but that is enough.
There are moments you strive to exceed the requested number of opponents (as in a classic race) then you run against the clock (classical dual with the chronometer) and then still awaits you another duel with an opponent.
From time to time you also have the police entering the game and trying to make the situation difficult for you.
The novelty is out-of-vehicle passages.
This is rather an interactive animation when most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by taping the right button at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
What is surprising is that there are fewer such moments than you expect (to be concrete, there are only three).
In the result, it is like this because this element is not likely to interfere and places itself, in the context described above, in the elements that embellish the game.
The driving model is in the tradition of previous games.
Which means there is nothing extraordinary right now, but it cannot be said to be negative.
For realistic simulation, you will need to go elsewhere.
But although one can find better in the competition the driving model goes very well with the type of race design.
So everything is OK.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
In contrast to the model of conduct, the collision model is not yet ready.
We do not expect from this game a complicated deformation and collisions, but when you do not have, in a collision with any object, any idea of how your car behaves, so it is not completely good.
During tight overtaking you sometimes touch each other slightly but otherwise your car part in crazy bumps.
Or find it in crumbs.
Thanks to the reboot system this is not really a problem but it really annoys you.
The restart is done in such a way that when you broke your face or you got out in the setting the game takes you back at the time of the last point on the route.
But you only have 5 reboots.
When you use the 5 restarts you have to start the game again from the start.
So it’s more a tool, in case something doesn’t go right, than something you can truly count on.
Sometimes reboots don't help and you have to find the solution by remembering from memory the piece of the route in question.
The biggest thing about this game is that the same actions are in the same places.
For example, there are some turns that need to be passed in a certain way otherwise this does not happen.
Otherwise you encounter "civil" vehicles in the same configuration as you arrived first, fifth, 5 seconds ahead or one minute late.
What makes you angry are situations when you easily see the opponent passing between two cars coming in the reverse direction and when you arrive, you have to either set aside and circumvent them or brake them.
