The Velvet Students in concert with the Charles University Choirs
The Festa Academica festival offers for the third time festivities that connect the International Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical part.
During the festival there are 20 choirs from high schools and secondary classes.
The nail of the festival consists of two concerts organised on November 17.
"Charles University has an important part in this festival."
"Among the choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and Humanities, in the committee of the festival sits the Rector Vaclav Hampl," says the head of the organizing team Jakub Calou.
The nail of the festival is the concert of the Choir of High Schools and Secondary Classes which takes place with free entry on November 17 from 2 p.m. on the space located in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
On the program there is the composition of well-known Czech jazzman Karel Ruzicka, Celebration Jazz mass.
In the evening the concert "Students of Velvet" takes place in the premises of the National House in Vinohrady, during which the choirs of the higher schools as well as the Charles University perform.
The aim of the Festa Academica is not only to celebrate International Student Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present the public with choir music of the highest level and to develop creative cooperation among young people.
The main organizer is the Union of Czech Cheers in cooperation with Jan Kepler High School.
The whole action is placed under the aegis of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Vaclav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The program also offers high-level concerts, msical meetings, a student happening and other activities.
Interested parties will find all the information on the internet pages of the festival www.festaacademica.cz.
Vicenova, Ambassador to the European Union:
The Czechs behave like negativists and eurosceptics
"The Lisbon Treaty radically suppressed balance between institutions"
“I didn’t expect such a tough war.”
"It will last 5.6 years before the situation calms down and all players get used to their new role," Milena Vicenova started her presentation at the Faculty of Law, the Czech Ambassador near the European Union.
When she succeeded in describing the various EU bodies and their relations in such a comprehensible and visible manner, to the point that a large number of speakers from the Charles University Law School could envy her, she showed how much she takes her motto "comprehensible and openly about Europe" very seriously.
Mrs Vicenova paid tribute to the work of Herman Van Rompuye, the new Permanent President of the European Council.
