The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the Ambassador, "the activity has beaten its full" not only for the Presidency but also for the financial crisis that continues to be resolved.
In addition, the new seven-year EU budget must be approved, which is becoming very complicated due to the current economic situation.
Since it seems that the budget will be slim and with a view to saving, which sector will have priority, which countries will be assisted the most, the least, everything is to be resolved in future negotiations.
The Ambassador recalled her slogans with which she arrived in Brussels "For a comprehensible Europe".
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words, jargons that no one understands.
As the citizen must understand, it is true that in Brussels no one makes round or twisted corniches, differently large bananas, or that no one has forbidden us from making syreckys."
It wants to better use the EU environment and see more Czechs in the EU institutions.
A multi-speed Europe awaits us
According to the Ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics and people who see things only in their negative aspect more than positively.
She is also sorry to see such a small Czech representation in the European institutions.
The fault, in her opinion, is due to several factors, such as the shyness of our candidates, their inability to write a letter of motivation and a low support from the Czech side.
In addition to a successful Czech Presidency, she then highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when the Polish, the Magyar, the Slovak come to me, this Frenchman says to me, 'Hey, what are you doing there, what else is this group of Visegrad doing?'
According to Mrs Vicenova, in the near future Member States will have tough new fiscal policy rules.
It is the concept of a two-speed Europe, if not a multi-speed Europe, that prevails rather than a "new European Federation".
“We have countries in the euro area and others outside the area.”
“We have the Schengen area, we also have the Institute for Enhanced Cooperation.”
First, it was said that countries that want to cooperate with each other and those that do not want to remain in their corners.
"There will be a lot of such institutes and there will be a really two-speed Europe," Mrs Vicenova expects.
From this point of view, it also appreciated the mission of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuye to determine the basis on which all themes that have an impact on the EU must be discussed among all EU members and not only the members of the eurozone.
History of a brand:
The IBM innovator begins the second century of its existence
If anyone was to look for the vocabulary that expresses the IBM strategy closest, the closest would be "the long term."
For a broad audience, IBM is the symbol of the technological revolution, is a firm felt as very current and yet since its creation it has passed a hundred years.
The foundation of this long-term strategy was laid by the company’s first leader, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He left this slogan that a large number of global problems can be solved for as little as people are willing to reflect.
His slogan "PENSE!" became the footprint around which the life of a giant future will develop (and also the title of the internal magazine that IBM began to publish in 1935).
This was the foundation of Watson's care company culture.
For us, IBM means a long-term thinking of continuous movements directed towards the future.
IBM survived a hundred years thanks to the fact that it remained true to its core values and nevertheless was not afraid to change all the others around it.
This has enabled us in our first century to transform technology, business and society.
We hope that in the second century we will reach even more"delayed for the birthday the current director of the company Samuel J. Palmisano.
A well-prepared system
Watson, in the 1930s, began taking care of his employees as Bata in the Czech Republic - the people at IBM were the only ones of the first American employees to have paid vacation, an employer-paid insurance plus an elegant employee uniform and a well-developed reward system for inventors and merchants.
Similarly, IBM has a well-developed customer relationship system.
The company was at first brilliant in the discovery of talent – as one of the first firms to have abolished all forms of discrimination and could thus have a choice.
The current plan is completely in the spirit of the anti-discrimination strategy since it will be a woman—Virginia Rometty—who should replace Palmisano at IBM’s head.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years and currently serves as Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has done what is known as jamy, brain storming online, from which a lot of future strategies and innovations have come.
It's no wonder he has a lot of ideas - in the firm there are nearly 500,000 people working.
An institution with a good name
