How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a western inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual travel was not permitted.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
Even after that, it wasn’t won yet.
The deal for currencies that was the condition for travelling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currency (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and cottages that the Czechs purchased and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, Czech travel has undergone a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at maximum, the Czechs spent abroad last year 4 million days vacation in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in western neighbouring countries has caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or pension.
The typical trait of a Czech trip at that time was to take with you your own food canned, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment has also been the interchangeability of the Czech crown which has finally allowed our tourists after decades of free buying Western currency.
Our standard of living and average wage increased, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
As a result of increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter routes since 1997, which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to previously.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully fit into the group of developed countries.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on vacation abroad including annexed charges.
