Peter Englund’s new book offers depth and generosity, entitled “The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War”, it begins with a long list of characters that tightens your heart.
A tip to get started: carefully rip this page and make it your bookmark.
In this romantic narrative by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mist of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, who awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book, which he accurately describes as "a book of anti-history."
It has a few known names, important treaties or famous battles; almost no ambassadors or discussions about strategies and materials are found.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like," it's the "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulances and sellers.
Some of them will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose members, go mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives waver here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguishing, new ones are re-fired.
Peter Englund's book deviates from traditional history books.
He denied the idea that World War I could only be summed up by the terrible trench war on the western front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tse-tse flies are an untreatable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural catastrophe, like a hurricane Katrina that smells cordite.
When gun shots sound in the distance, and you are a mother of the household, do you stay or flee?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been enhanced by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
"Beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high sea fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are more preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most are dealing with deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, überall Ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on replacement food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; soles of wooden shoes."
He states that "837 substitute meats are registered in the sausage production. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories address honor and courage.
An American acknowledges his own impulse towards savagery and states about war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant to do, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a best-seller, and rather than pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that it has no bars.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is at risk of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention to it.
“When one is resigned to sacrifice oneself, one hopes to have an audience,” he wrote.
This is unfortunately rather comparable to “a convicted man strangled in secret.”
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
“Conflict is increasingly becoming a history of economic competition,” writes Peter Englund, “a war between factories.”
He grasps the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the bestiary of the beginning of the century: the well-articulated and ideologically convinced mass murderer, in well-cut clothes, who executes his butchery while sitting behind a counter."
