Walls Have Eyes: Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy sharing his anti-immigration opinions online.
On Monday, Breivik, who acknowledged he was caught from a deadly madness in Norway in July, leaving 77 victims, was faced with his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, chatting with a few of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easily... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t so difficult to find them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, Jamie Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they are looking for with scientific accuracy – the way merchants have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes toward violence and their optimism about their own future.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: the online supporters of the right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new tool in the hands of scientists.
Thinking groups, medicine researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "Like", wall-based publications and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three contents per day, the “data supernova” generates a search explosion, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by nearly 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to investigate the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter," Bartlett said.
"Facebook avoids all of this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their intoxicated exploits were much more likely to be alcoholic than discrete students about it.
Megan Moreno suggested that colleagues from the students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and eventually intervene to help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics regarding the valentine's day and love situation, the participation rate in the 2010 mid-term elections and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available - digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is quite another thing online.
"I don't think a large number of users have ever thought that a researcher could study their profile," said Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study will be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you’re saying on Facebook and what you’re doing in reality are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and a pen remain the best tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people," he said.
“Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect – and the social aspect is not in front of a computer.”
