After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical engineer and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will be aired this week in the first part of a film on major markets, is how much this creative spirit had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organizational chart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a genius exception.
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat down for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years since Steve Jobs had to leave Apple and was already working hard on his new NeXT IT company, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transportation.
It is only after Steve Jobs’ death that a full video is found in the director’s garage.
This slightly uphill video is the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be aired in theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems here surprisingly excited to expose technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide an accurate answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbow kicks to speed him up and move on to issues or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strange aspect of Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and expresses his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“For all these years, I’ve always been asking, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same, ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues giving details on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed about how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" rated at the nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour at the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack phone networks and phone for free on long distances.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs's euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you screamed in the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door," Jobs said laughing.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't know much about both of us, but we were able to invent a little thing capable of controlling great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful round that he and Wozniak developed: he called the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two complicites laugh crazy just before the Pope himself is awakened.
About his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s departure):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and calls him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company’s research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first desktop computer ever designed.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was returned to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On improvisation of innovation:
At several times in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a head-to-head.
At the beginning of his career, as he sets up to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big quarrels... I was screamed at me pretending it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I got enough, I got out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that proved incredibly reliable.
On the large companies that are breathing out:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would be mistaken and lose control of their market share.
"Let's admit that you worked at IBM or Xerox, do you make a better copy or printer, and then?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not have more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [those are these types of people] that end up leading businesses and product-specialized staff are put away from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product in comparison to a bad product - the manual work required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have made ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They took the defeat from the victory.
Innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge portion of manual work separates a great idea from an outstanding product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to do... Some things you can’t do, electrons can do, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (those concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product you're creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dinner with health law adversaries as court meets
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to discuss the issue of political disagreement, namely whether the opposition to President Obama’s health law will be heard, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were noticed at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will defend the case in the High Court.
The event was last Thursday, when the nine judges gathered for a conference to discuss petitions for consideration.
One of the cases involved a trial filed by 26 states contesting the ambitious health care reform voted by Congress last year, a law that has been a gathering point for conservative activists at the national level.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, indeed, a monumental 5:30 a.m. argument is expected next March, and the result will likely be of a nature to favor the destabilization of the 2012 presidential race, which will be booming at the time the court’s decision will be rendered.
The lawyer who will stand in court and argue about the rejection of the law will probably be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. solicitor general during the administration of George W. Bush.
Clément’s law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was one of the two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another promoter was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which presents a huge financial issue in the outcome of the dispute.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court conference on the case.
There was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the top Republican of the Senate and declared adversary of the health law.
The guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: the two judges have been present at the events of the Federalist Society for years.
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would doubtfully argue by the Canon 4C code, which states: "A judge may attend fundraising from law-related organizations and others although the judge may not be an intervener, an honor guest, or appearing on the program of such an event."
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas near two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
“This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the Court respects the same rules applicable to all other federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were drinking and dining and at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending in court."
Their presence and participation in the fundraising of this event dismantles any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little respect for critics claiming that they were too easily mixing court affairs with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’s wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, the Conservatives claim that it is Judge Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was a solicitor general for Obama's administration when the first oppositions to the law were brought at the trial level.
Her critics pushed for Kagan to refuse to hear the case, saying she had invested too much in defending the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would.
Boeing records $18 billion order for aircraft
The airline Emirates orders 50 Boeing 777, two-courier aircraft, with the possibility of buying 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Oman Air, a market estimated at more than $1 billion.
There is nothing extraordinary about a company receiving an order that includes 50 of its products.
This is a case when the company in question is the manufacturer of Boeing aircraft and the amount of these 50 aircraft reaches a record $18 billion.
Equally incredible is who Boeing received this order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a forecast released Monday, the Chicago airline estimates that Middle Eastern airlines will need 2,520 planes worth $450 billion in the next 20 years.
During the weekend, Boeing informed of the most expensive commercial aircraft order in its history - 50 Boeing 777 bi-corridors.
It is Emirates airline based in Dubai who placed this pharaonic order.
Boeing announced at the Dubai Aviation Show in 2011 that the airline is also likely to buy 20 more aircraft, raising the total order amount to $26 billion.
On the other hand, Boeing said Monday that Oman Air has ordered six Boeing 787-8, nicknamed Dreamliners, a model that flatters significant fuel savings and passenger conveniences.
The amount of these six aircraft amounts to more than $1 billion.
“It’s clearly very positive for Boeing,” said Neal Dihora, an analyst at Morningstar.
“These customers in particular have immense value.”
In the Middle East, oil producing countries own many of their airlines.
They therefore not only have the means to pay for these planes, but a rise in fuel prices - usually harmful to airlines as it represents their largest expenses - would not be so harmful to them as the country would earn money with the rise in oil prices.
This is an important point because these airlines will be less likely than others to cancel or delay their aircraft orders as oil prices rise, Dihora reported.
“They have natural risk coverage,” he said.
The Emirates order reinforces Boeing’s predominance in the large-scale aircraft market and helps curb the attempted intrusion of the competitor Airbus with its A350 aircraft.
Boeing’s victory at the aeronautical show comes four months after Airbus announced to postpone the debut of the largest version of the A350, which directly competes with the Boeing 777-300ER.
Airbus is pushing its debut to increase its push following the demand of its customers to increase its load capacity and autonomy.
Boeing’s shares increased by 1.5% to $67.94.
Mexican President's sister clearly beaten in Michoacán elections
Luisa Maria Calderon says the drug traffickers helped his opponent Fausto Vallejo of the PRI in the race as governor.
President Felipe Calderon's sister appears to have lost her attempt to access the posts of governor of Michoacán during violent elections, and she said Monday that drug traffickers have favored one of her opponents.
The first results indicated that Fausto Vallejo of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was at the forefront of the race as the governor of this state of the west.
“The intervention of organized crime throughout the voting process and especially yesterday is an alarming fact, not only for Michoacán but for the whole country,” Luisa Maria Calderon told the radio in an interview Monday following the elections.
“They threatened our candidates, our electoral officers... They seized the polls, set up road blocks... and forced people to vote” for the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seventy years until losing the presidency in 2000.
But he is organizing his return, and a victory in Michoacán is an important step in this effort.
The PRI hopes to win the presidential election in July.
Vallejo seems to have spotted only a few of Calderon, who was at the forefront of the polls before the election day.
Calderon, a candidate for his brother’s conservative party, the National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, a left-wing candidate of the Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, who currently holds the position of governor, arrived third, a painful defeat before the 2012 presidential election for this divided and unhappy left.
Aureoles also refused to acknowledge the first results.
