Michoacán has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in the trafficking of marijuana, heroin and methamphetamine.
It is the state of origin of President Calderon, and he chose the Michoacán to launch a military offensive against traffickers in December 2006.
Nevertheless, violence has persisted.
A week before the elections, a mayor of the PAN was murdered while campaigning for Luisa Maria Calderon, and many candidates resigned locally to the campaign out of fear.
However, for the PRI, as corrupt as the Michoacán elections look, a victory will help the party in its momentum.
The man waiting to represent the PRI in the presidential race, Enrique Pena Nieto, congratulated Vallejo from Washington and said, "I think this victory is very encouraging in view of next year."
BASD strongly urges Asia to help the euro area
The Asian Development Bank has called on India and China to prepare to help the euro area get out of the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term decline that would prevent the development of the Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, Manila-based BASD chief executive, said the two fastest-growing economic powers in the world must "do everything in their power" to speed up the recovery of the monetary zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He advised BRICs (Brazil, Russia, India, China) not to look at Europe's difficulties with an "indifferent eye" and pointed out that Asian financial support alongside Europe's leaders and resources would prevent a long-term collapse of the global economy.
“We are all together in this crisis.”
“So anyone who can help Europe get out of the crisis is helpful,” he told the Financial Times during an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia can be protected to a certain extent, but it is not safe."
“So if China and India can help, nothing will stop them.”
In recent months, the euro area has been seriously shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of Italian borrowing has risen dangerously and the Prime Ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The flourishing sovereign debt crisis in Europe has sparked fear that the world economy will go into recession, and has sparked the call of major emerging economies to come together to help the euro area find a solution.
Mr. Nag predicted that the IMF would deliver any Asian aid, but he also said that this bilateral aid - such as buying the bonds of the U.S. financial rescue fund, the European Financial Stability Fund - offered greater negotiating power to Asian partners in Europe.
Indian Trade and Industry Minister Anand Sharma said that "India will do everything it can" to help the euro area as its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a drying inflow of foreign capital.
“No one wants the euro area to remain unstable and unrestled,” he said.
“We have monumental challenges to face and we need to maintain a high level of growth.”
“It’s not a choice, it’s an imperative, because where would we find work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?”
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help the wealthy Europeans while facing their own major economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said it would be politically very difficult to get aid to Europe to the 1.2 billion Indians, of whom at least 800,000 live with $2 a day or less.
“One day, they will find out that the Greeks retire at age 50 and go on vacation in the sun and they will have trouble swallowing it,” he said.
Lee Howell, the president of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India's reserves should be used to keep many well-paid Greek officials in poorly managed jobs that generate losses, such as in the railway sector.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis risked causing "significant repercussions" across Asia.
BASD's forecast of a 7.5% economic growth in Asia in 2011/2012 is now facing "risks of loss" due to the European threat.
He noted that vulnerable emerging markets need to develop "rescue plans" to protect themselves from economic shifts and significant capital leaks.
Severe Pentagon warnings about potential defense reductions
Defence Secretary Leon Panetta raised pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that imminent automatic budget compressions would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from Pentagon corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields, through civilian gatherings.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in reductions for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 or more compression will be imminent if Congress fails to reach a spending agreement.
“The impacts of these reductions would be devastating for the ministry,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting from what is called sequestration would result in 23% reductions as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"A reduction of such a size, applied thus undistingly, would make most of our ships and construction projects unenforceable - you cannot buy three-quarters of a ship or building - and seriously damage other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We would also be forced to separate a number of our civilian staff and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we almost certainly should send civilians on unpaid leave in order to achieve the goal."
“These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparation.”
The reductions would eventually affect the fighting troops, continues Panetta.
"Although wartime financing of the accounts of contingency operations abroad is not directly affected by the sequestration, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disturbances in the basic budgets," Panetta warned.
“Contracting staff would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of contracts that support the war.”
“Wage-managing staff would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to war providers, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details about the potential impact of automatic compression on the Ministry of Defense.
“The consequence of a sequestration on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as an undisputed world leader of military power.”
"We are strongly opposed to this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon during the publication of Panetta's letter.
“It is not a consequence that we can live with, and it is certainly not the one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen.”
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators are increasing pressure for a budget compromise or an appeal to exempt the Pentagon from reductions remains to be seen.
Panetta has become more and more virulent about possible compressions, even though he himself reached the highest position of the Pentagon accumulating years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing that he was facing difficult choices.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a dark picture of what could happen - a military with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a bulletless brigade."
"It's a fighter plane, without enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don’t have enough trained soldiers capable of carrying out the mission,” Panetta said in his preliminary remarks to the Pentagon.
“It’s a depressed force, poorly prepared and unable to cope with potential opponents.”
"In fact, she invites to aggression."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further reductions could "generate significant operational risks: delay in response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits to our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable risk in future combat operations."
And Panetta said some of the largest defense projects could move to the cutter, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a new planned bomber, the next generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat vessel and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Humvee of the army and navy.
Putting an end to the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is an essential step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Identify a Lie
A look at the recent headlines indicates how omnipresent deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy sharing allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators were accused of false sworn in allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone stating to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lie has destroyed quarries and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, made himself an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violations of funding campaigns related to the coverage of an extramarital liaison.
And then, none of those who lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The narratives of cheating at the school and university tests are a legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave test responses to students in order to show themselves well on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout: "I've had you," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data gathered over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, including in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been demystified.
Liars are looking in your eyes.
They don’t tick, red, or stir up always.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial micro-expression, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include including hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are skilled in reading others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is called "establishing the benchmark data".
This helps provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs his feet constantly so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him stir his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal misleading behaviour.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, significantly change posture, or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson scraped off using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use distant language: "I didn't have sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or fully repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be true... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial Oil Pipeline Plan Will Be Distorted After U.S. Threat of Late Approval
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay the approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico - sparking anger from trade unions while calming environmentalists - the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is ready to redirect the project to put it back on track.
TransCanada said Monday night that it will move the projected pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive area of the Nebraska dunes, and is confident that the project will still win its approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Capitol of Nebraska.
TransCanada official Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident that it will eventually obtain the approval of a pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the State Department's announcement last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal license for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid areas of the Nebraska dunes and Ogallala watershed, large groundwater sources.
“It’s a real path forward,” Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, told Fox News.
The re-environmental review commissioned by the Department of State would probably have postponed any decision until 2013, after next year's elections, although officials deny the policy involvement in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department’s decision, and expressed its support.
The 2,735 km pipeline would extend from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would transport 700,000 barrels a day from Alberta Province to Texas Refineries.
In order to do so, it would have to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, who have bet on the 20,000 estimated jobs related to the pipeline.
But the Nebraska lawmakers opposed to this plan put pressure on a law to force the removal of the Sand Hills region and the Ogallala Aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The Department of State's ongoing Environmental Impact Study found that the project would only have limited negative environmental impacts, but the energy industry stated that the Department's Inspector General ordered a separate investigation of the review process, focused on two issues.
One is that a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was a campaign advisor to Hillary Clinton in 2008, would represent a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a company that was hired to conduct the initial study was an inappropriate choice by its relationship with TransCanada.
