The Court validates "analog cut-off" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) disputed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Deputies formulated against the presidential decree advancing the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes needed to invalidate it were not gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to realise the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not having reached a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because radio and television regulations are a statutory assignment reserved to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and law reserve.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of ministers also resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the House of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister-President said he disagreed with the arguments of the draft, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards measures for the public administration to prepare for them.
"I don't think that if it were done it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the leadership of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this results in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, “because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These questions, he stressed, "requires the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic leadership of the State, encompasses a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State."
He recalled that many countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in some way the sphere of competence of Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote-by-vote" count is being analyzed in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second places of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6,000 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second places of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
It will be remembered that Michoacán did not approve neither his Political Constitution nor his State Electoral Code nor his Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the Congress of the State had approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process to come into force, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the time prescribed by the Offician.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called “invalid and unlawful” the vote of the state’s representative for constitutional reforms, because he has no right to “sanction or challenge them.”
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that through the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no voting record and counting in the file of the urn is not found in the president of the urn; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all election polls may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the supposed winner of the respective election and the one who won the second place in the poll is equal to or below a percentage point presented; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the second party or the party.
The total counting of the vote may also be carried out if at the end of the joint counting, the difference between the supposed winner and that of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party from which the candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages that were the subject of the counting are excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second places is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
