The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government facing a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form the government.
It is expected that he presents a cabinet composed in his majority of technocrats, even though it is unclear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner for Journalists said.
Monti did not explicitly state that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well traced,” he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels that cannot be sustained.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the affected trust in Italy.
Emphasizing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success have been greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic-majority government that Monti formed.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday consultations with political parties, trade unions and employer groups and youth and women’s organizations.
He will finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist until the future elections scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections advances.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual suspicion and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
