"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of the impact," he says.
During the press conference, TBS holder, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM mentioned adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft moved towards the border zone between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-height cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloud conditions the crew sought a lower height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was neither loss of control nor alteration of the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information so far available makes it possible to assume that the impact took place on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the remains of the aircraft makes it possible to assume that the helicopter has hit the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the place of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest investigation results indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the ground showed a slope that ranged from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in an area larger than the surrounding area, there were no dispersed parts of the aircraft found, supporting the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Gene of Obesity
