The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and youth, called the 'Genetic Protocol for Obesity in Children and Adolescents' that will have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialities of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the entitled or unentitled population to participate in the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence to minors takes place every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that it is to know the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and youth between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometrical measurements (weight, height, size circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic measurements will be applied to all participants (seeking to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity in the case of boys and 47 per cent in the case of girls; also a dramatic increase in overweight," the IMSS specialist stressed.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65% Indo-American inheritance, 30% European and 5% African inheritance, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translate into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which deposits itself in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows to detect whether they are overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle that they must take to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (scales - corn flour meat paste wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and genetically analyzed in this.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cracking
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis per rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the pavement is completely eliminated, the cassis could be reduced.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory of which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with similar characteristics to that of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures of nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has a near solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes breaking, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers lies the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he notes, is bathed an asphalt.
When the vehicles pass through by generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, the chemical engineer would think.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer is placed called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion on the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer, it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all layers of the pavement and consequently causes bristles.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first that spoils is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle loading is another important factor in cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to vehicle loading and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to be investigated and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it easy to repair casks without having to use high temperatures.
