This was the work of the Cali person who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
A dactyloscopist from Cali has gone into history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a dactyloscopist from the CTI of Cali went to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprinters working in the local offices of the CTI, this week was the "availability" round of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of frictional skin, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the corpse, he did not recognize it by his physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But the fingerprints are not lying.
Accompanied by a Galtonian glass, ink, picker and lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the card.
His eye didn't deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
The same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In search of the footprint
For a dactyloscopist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave Eliazar González in a press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
Many people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, fingerprinters support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false ID cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search for them in the database.
The researcher said that in a case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had pushed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to get a fingerprint from them, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint from the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in various thefts," he recalls.
The fingerprints may also discard or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspected of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it places him on the scene of the crime.
A dactyloscopist from the CTI said that the fingerprints of objects were extracted with chemical or physical reagents.
When they appear, a picker or strip is used to remove them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the declining database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is how it is shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything that is touched does not forcefully become a footprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is carried out.
The "indignated" challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were shooting in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
Much of the people accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, through a court order, the Manhattan square, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Great Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were shooting in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a court order that allows the “indignated” to camp again in that place, while the other part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new arrests.
“Our idea is that if the court doesn’t allow us to camp again in the square, we’re going to settle elsewhere and we’re going to continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful protests,” said one of the spokespersons for the Occupy Wall Street movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the ‘indignated’ response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the camp and allowing protesters to stay in the camp.
Furthermore, the ‘indignated’ occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested a few protesters, even though Bray was unable to confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization says that there were hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the movement and tried to intervene in their favor before the Police.
In the meantime, Zuccotti square - which is a privately owned fortress - remains closed pending a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of the evacuation this morning is to be analysed.
A few displaced protesters were carrying and distributing copies of the court order at that time and they even handed it over to officers watching the square, which caused “some small clashes,” Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials struck the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or applying laws published after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from accessing the park again with tents or other properties they used before.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that because of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, but he warned them that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn at Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the protesters were "in violation of the law."
Bloomberg said he had given orders to evacuate the place because it was becoming “a place where people came not to protest, but to violate laws and in some cases to harm other people,” because “some shops had received threats” and residents were afraid “for their quality of life.”
“The evacuation this morning at dawn has been disgusting and demonstrates that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers,” said the movement’s spokesman, who accused the mayor of “not respecting freedom of expression.”
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they did not plan to organize "big actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions to commemorate the two-month protests, which began on September 17.
