GDP rises by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends declining spiral in early March
Since March the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe in the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo calculated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page definitively: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to a 0.9% decline in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to changing domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen – the Japanese currency – became one of the “refuge values” elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the U.S. forecasting unrest, a privilege that weighs like a tile in the accounts of exporting companies.
