Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, expert committee says
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions, and doctors to work together to provide better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from various fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where necessary, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
From the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the planet.
If Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada report.
And despite the desire most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, Quebec has the highest rate, with 86% of hospital deaths.
On the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where such approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, said yesterday, there would be more cases of these overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
“Euthanasy is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.”
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” Downie said.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of respondents estimate that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing care with a patient, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that withdrawal of care for which there was a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The expert committee also requests that health professionals be trained to respect an end-of-life refusal of care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions, and doctors to work together to provide better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, in terms of palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that it be considered, where it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some health law experts have already made reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada expert report.
Mr Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signatory to the report "extreme," inter alia because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to terminally ill patients.
“This opens the door to a situation where anyone who would be tired of life and over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide,” said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Me Deschamps also emphasizes that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"In society," he said, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called "pro-euthanasy manifestation."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, in particular challenges the report’s data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, in the Netherlands and Oregon.
