Bashar al-Assad’s supporters demonstrated yesterday in front of the Foreign Ministry’s premises.
Diplomatic pressures intensified yesterday on Bashar al-Assad’s Syria, which, with the support of Russia, resists them and denounces a “complot” against the country.
Two days after the Arab League’s suspension of Syria, the European Union strengthened its sanctions against Damascus while Turkey and Jordan, neighbours of Syria, took a position in favour of President Assad’s departure.
Jordan’s King Abdullah II was yesterday the first Arab leader to call on President Bashar al-Assad to “leave power” in Syria where about forty civilians and members of the regime’s forces were still killed.
“If Bashar had the interests of his country at heart, he should resign, but he should also create the necessary conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life,” the king of Jordan, Syria’s neighbor, told the BBC.
For his part, Turkish diplomatic leader Ahmet Davutoglu deplored that the Turkish mediation efforts undertaken with the Syrian regime since the beginning of the year have resulted in a failure.
"Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their peoples and cannot satisfy them will leave," he said, referring to Syria, a neighbouring country with which Turkey is adopting an increasingly harder line.
The United States congratulated itself on a "strengthening of consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime" following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
“The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey are adopting an increasingly harder tone” in the face of repression in Syria, observed State Department spokesman Mark Toner.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime's forces have died in the Deraa region in southern Syria, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSHR) announced.
Two other civilians have been killed "in exchanges of fire and pistoling with heavy machine guns in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Mouallem said the country was "towards the end of the crisis".
He also strongly reacted to the Arab League’s decision to suspend Damascus from its work, which he believes is “a dangerous step”.
Syria "will not bend," he added, assuring that "the Urdi conspiracies against Syria will fail."
Following its decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now studying a "civil protection mechanism" and wishes to send 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, media and military observers in the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé has also expressed his support for the sending of UN observers to help protect civilians from the crackdown of the regime that he believes is enclosed in "paranoia".
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled to be held tomorrow in Rabat to review the implementation of the crisis exit plan decided on November 2, including the withdrawal of the armed forces from the cities facing the protest and the release of the arrested protesters.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov deemed the Arab League's decision "incorrect" yesterday, while China urged Syria to implement the crisis exit plan, while refraining from supporting possible sanctions against Damascus.
Italy's
Monti demands time for markets and sacrifices for Italians
The future Italian government chief Mario Monti has demanded some time in the markets to form his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifices," in order to regain the credibility lost in the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in discussions with the political parties yesterday before meeting the unions and the employers today.
It should set up a relatively narrow cabinet consisting of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important program with many sacrifices," said Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many small parliamentary groups engaged in the interviews, after meeting with the appointed President of the Council.
Chairman of the House of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, said he expects Mario Monti to seek a vote of confidence in Parliament by Friday to ensure that the new government has sufficient support.
The consultations will conclude with the submission by Mr Monti of a limited list, probably a dozen ministers, to the Head of State, Giorgio Napolitano.
Monti commented on the nervousness of stock and bond markets yesterday, asking for time.
In "democracy, there are precise deadlines" for preparing a government and its program, he stressed, saying "certainly that markets will be patient and will understand."
His appointment by the president had initially been welcomed by the markets, but concerns took over, especially after an unexpected drop in industrial production in the euro area in September.
The appointed Prime Minister should form a team consisting mainly of technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "politics".
The new government is expected to last until 2013, the date of the upcoming legislative elections, he said.
According to House Chairman Gianfranco Fini, the new government will gain Parliament’s trust by Friday.
Monti pledged, once he entered office, to work in an emergency and with the aim that Italy "redeved itself as a protagonist" in Europe.
A spokesman for EU Commissioner Olli Rehn stressed that "even with a new government, our diagnosis of the Italian economy does not change."
The EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its fiscal balance target in 2013 despite the austerity plans adopted in recent months, has called for further rigorous measures.
The Italian "sponsor of boss" Emma Marcegaglia, who will see it on Tuesday, also stressed the need to relaunch the economy, "because a country that has no growth cannot comply with deficit parameters."
Monti, renowned for his competence and independence as European Commissioner (1994-2004), represents a "changing epoch" for Italy after 17 years of "berlusconism", the "teacher" symbolizing "the challenge of seriousness" and an "other Italy", according to the editorialists.
The biggest unknown will be the longevity of his team.
President Napolitano would like to avoid early elections, as Italy must put up by April 2012 for €200 billion in state bonds.
Russian Scientist Helped Iran's Nuclear Program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, helped Iran develop a detonator that could be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in nuclear hazard said on Monday.
The Institute for International Science and Security (ISIS) relies on the recent report of the International Agency for Atomic Security (IAEA) and other documents from this UN agency to identify this researcher.
The IAEA last week expressed its "serious concerns" about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to ISIS, drawing extensively from IAEA documents, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, reportedly worked for three decades from the 1960s at a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk, Ural, and reportedly was involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he allegedly left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
The economic difficulties of his company would have led him to contact the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He would then cooperate on the Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA refers to "strong indication that Iran's development of a nuclear detonation system "was helped by the work of a foreign expert, who not only knew well about this technique, but who, as a member state informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear program of his home country."
Anti-Muslim crimes and crimes increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims increased by nearly 50% from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, other racial and religious violence decreased slightly or did not progress, according to FBI statistics released on Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence against Muslims rose from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, up 49%, compared with a 13% increase in violence against Catholics, a 4% decrease in crimes against Jews and an overall 14% increase in anti-religious crimes and crimes.
The total number of “hate crimes” has increased very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3% are motivated by race differences and 20% by religion differences, according to the FBI.
“After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and crimes rise again,” the human rights organization underlined, “the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant,” the organization added in a statement.
“Human Rights First has long emphasized that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be seen as a serious violation of human rights,” said Paul Legendre, one of the organization’s officials.
“The U.S. government can and must do more to address these abuses,” he added, saying that this could be through an improvement in police reports on “hate crimes.”
The “hate crime” in U.S. federal law is a legacy of the era of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation had been passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, skin color, religion, origin and now sexual affiliation.
