Austrian
the inclusion of a budgetary "gold rule" in the Constitution
The large-scale social-democratic/Christian-Democratic ruling coalition in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a "gold rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision after a council of ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Treaty of Maastricht, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were to be reduced by only one cran, from AAA to AA+, we should pay three billion euros in additional interest each year,” said Deputy Chancellor and Christian Democratic Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the summit in Brussels of the euro area on 26 October: the heads of state and government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The arrangement adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit will have to decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017, the federal government’s structural public deficit will not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present budgets in balance.
The aim is to increase public debt by 2020/21 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
