Energy policy:
The facts must override the dogmas.
If it is a topic that cannot be dealt with from short-term considerations or emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an electoral appointment is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear power.
The debate will only be successful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic evolution will lead to a double of electricity demand by 2050, unless it deprives a huge portion of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity on an ongoing basis, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate disruption, a disappeared issue of the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear.
This is not the case with Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor with Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name them alone, are continuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island crash.
While the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in the increased price of electricity, an increased energy dependence due to the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a leap in CO2 emissions resulting from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all of these bad effects are already felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated.
European wind champion, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; according to which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher respectively than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the continuity of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction on the part of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power illusory.
A price that a vast majority of French people refuse to pay, especially as they do not express opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
Remember that our country’s energy policy has helped to build an industrial chain of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 jobs created.
Heavily exporting, it drives a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them very creative for jobs that cannot be relocated.
If France decided to leave nuclear, it would sacrifice many of these small and medium-sized enterprises by reducing as a skin of grief the 6 billion euros annually of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years when its manufacturer’s decline would be programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
The development by Areva of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear, maintaining the highest level of security is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the construction site in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human mistakes caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two unprecedented natural disasters that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift given to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the way to seize leadership in the unmistakable development of nuclear.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate a debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the engagement of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "the country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus between left and right on this topic.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "9000000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't welcome all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as well as the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande has a banality, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps electorally paying; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recalled in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among immigrants receiving the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and impairing employment.
Fears of the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants risk substituting domestic workers, especially those with low skills, putting downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly in jobs in sectors with shortages of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the highest-skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow job offers.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants cause immigrant arrivals to have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the U.S. Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of 150000 euros to public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to pick up the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, being used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought of
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to ultimately triumph over its enemies to vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way.
It is known, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, in order to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the prerequisite and can even become an “instrument of oppression” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first a crisis of politics and democracy.
In this regard, the palinidy of the true-false Greek referendum will have been double-revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have been displaced today, and for many of them Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to necessities and in dispersed order.
A white-seing with the absolute European monarch or a foot jump joined in the void of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but a common, rightful, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we can no longer stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that folds to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to restore the leadership of the European project to popular sovereignty.
It is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will imply decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless of course they lead us to disaster.
After long fighting against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for the European Economic Government.
Yeah, yeah.
But thinking of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
In order to make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" the Republicans.
The Revolution in Interest could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a true European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let’s make Europeans.
