The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia passing to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brightly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the banks of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly links underwater Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km pipe connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomeranian Land.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And it is already mentioned the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion of this huge construction site in time and time seems to be a victory.
The project was strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow the delivery of gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of weakening the energy Europe, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, highly gas-consuming, whose deposits are declining.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically,” confirmed François Fillon by opening this pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by Gazprom leaders, present in number at Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete coated steel to protect it against the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the seabed, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“A hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed, by precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is deemed unlikely by manufacturers who have planned welding for leakage every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft circulating within the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, wide one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, he provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, all of the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing for the construction of the pipeline was 30% secured by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back into their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which designates a cotton polished used to cover seats, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
"Moleskine brought to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has become head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, now has almost 100 and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her booklets in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in downtown and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have been following the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies Moleskine's development: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand can be found on a wide range of supports.
A success that made envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Disabled begins today.
Despite a voluntary public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Disheartening?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt, the association that organizes the Week for the Employment of Disabled people.
“The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.”
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"Nevertheless, there is still a lot to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are many obstacles that remain before entering employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and out of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, so many criteria that singularly complicate the return to employment, and that "are the node of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for the objective brakes.
The unsaid remains, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entrepreneur pour la Cité indicated that the managers surveyed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "over-representation of wheelchair people, mentally impaired or intellectuals".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, which date from 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Managing Director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies,” says Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of institutions of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of companies of 100 to 199 employees.
